Re: Very good!


30 Apr 2017 06:36






The blackboxing is an intentional stylistic choice. Specifically, a lot of the blackboxes (and other censors) conceal names inspired by (or lifted from) reality. As implied by my opening post, this is partially inspired by real people and events. So the censor here serves three purposes:

Limit the possibility of connections being made between the reality and the fiction
Imply that the Foundation is trying to prevent the equivalent from happening in-universe (so, say, an agent stationed near SCP-2739 won't go and murder this dude's parents for child abuse, using his status as a Foundation agent to remain secret)
This stuff happens all the damn time, all over the place. I didn't want to apply an identity to these characters so it might be easier for the readers to apply their own; these people could be from a major city, or a small town. They could be from the desert or the coast or the mountains or anywhere in-between. They could be black, white, hispanic, Middle-Eastern, Native American, or any other conceivable ethnic/race category. They could be gay, straight, bi, closeted (or unacknowledged by the Foundation as) transgender, or fall into a category outside the easily-defined spectrum of gender  sexuality. These people could be anybody. These kinds of struggles don't know any real boundary. I wanted to make a point of letting the reader form an image in their own mind of who these people are.


I hate overuse of the censor when it's arbitrary, but I didn't feel it was arbitrary here.







